item.content:
&lt;p&gt;
	So you&amp;#39;ve played acoustic music all your life, but you&amp;#39;re just getting into plugging in. You went and bought a Les Paul or a Strat and you&amp;#39;re ready to rock, but how in the world do you start picking amps and pedals? If you don&amp;#39;t already have an electric guitar amp, it can be super-confusing to figure out how to spend your hard earned money. You plugged into 20 different amps at Guitar Center and you&amp;#39;re more frustrated now than before you started. I know the feeling... I&amp;#39;ve owned a lot of amps, from Fenders to Marshalls, with Vox, Peavey, Orange, Mesa, and Egnater along the way trying to find that &amp;#39;tone&amp;#39;. More than that, I&amp;#39;ve played pretty much everything in the marketplace because I&amp;#39;m OCD like that!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	All the gear guides I&amp;#39;ve read assume you&amp;#39;re either playing to big clubs and want to be really loud or you only play in the bedroom and just want the perfect tone at apartment levels. They&amp;#39;ll recommend 4-channel Mesa Road Kings or Marshall Half-Stacks or Fender Twin Reverbs. They&amp;#39;ll split hairs between 2 watt Class A amps with 8&amp;quot; speakers. That&amp;#39;s all fine and well if you are in those demographics - a lot of people are!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	But what if you require boutique tone, want to record and play at home, but also need to play small to medium-sized gigs? Playing small clubs requires more juice than a 5w amp can give you. By the same token, you aren&amp;#39;t interested in lugging a half-stack or a 60lb combo to your 30 person gig, only to turn that Marshall stack or Twin Reverb to volume &amp;quot;1&amp;quot;. A solid-state modeling amp is light and portable and can get plenty loud, but you&amp;#39;ll never get complements on your tone with one. Not that I&amp;#39;m a tube snob (the Roland Jazz Chorus is one of my all-time favorite amps) but a Line 6 (or insert whatever manufacturer here) modeling amp that promises &amp;quot;Blackface Cleans and High Gain crunch&amp;quot; from the same circuitboard just isn&amp;#39;t going to give you either. If you want effects, buy the best pedals for them. The only effects you want for sounds like delay, flanger, wah, chorus, etc are attained by buying a purpose-specific pedal. Do not buy multi-effect pedals either - I&amp;#39;ve tried many of them and SURE, they can give me high-gain distortion with chorus and flanger and auto-wah at the same time but they&amp;#39;ve always fallen short in the tone department (and do you ever really need that?).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	If you fit this profile, there&amp;#39;s really only two routes you want to go: an &lt;strong&gt;All-in-One&lt;/strong&gt; super-amp or &lt;strong&gt;Perfect Cleans Plus Pedals&lt;/strong&gt;. We&amp;#39;ll be looking at how to get the heavenly tone we want for rock, blues, country, jazz, and indie music.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;
	The All-In-One Route&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	For the person that wants everything cohesive and doesn&amp;#39;t want a pedalboard that&amp;#39;s 6 feet long, you can&amp;#39;t beat the baby Mesa amps.&amp;nbsp;These amps do it all. glistening cleans, cleans with a little dirt, full-on overdrive, and high-gain distortion. All-tube, Tube reverb, much lighter than full-size amps by same manufacturers, portable form factor but still loud enough for small and medium sized venues, footswitchable channels... everything you need an amp to do.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Recommend: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/RectoVerb112CB/&quot;&gt;Mesa Boogie Rectoverb 25&lt;/a&gt; (New $1250) &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F0bcGSZsd2A&quot;&gt;demo&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	Recommend: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/Exp525pls112&quot;&gt;Mesa Boogie Express 5:25&lt;/a&gt; (New: $1350 Used: $900+) &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nz3gHJ73P48&quot;&gt;demo&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Both of these amps are 2 channels and each channel has 2 voices, reasonable volume (Rectoverb, each channel can be 10w or 25w. 5:25 can be 5w, 10w. or 25w), both have a 1x12&amp;quot; speaker that records well, and has that made in USA quality. Both also can drive an external cabinet if you need to move a bit more air in bigger venues. Bonus: Mesa products retain their value.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Similar to these is the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/Rebel30112&quot;&gt;Egnater Rebel 30&lt;/a&gt; (New: $900 Used: $500) ...it&amp;#39;s discontinued, but has many of the same features as the Mesas as well as some extra recording features (silent recording switch, balanced out, 6V6/EL84 tube mix knob) Guitar Center is the best place to find used Egnater gear because their brand name isn&amp;#39;t super well known.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;
	Amp and Pedals Route&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The secret to great electric guitar tone is just like any recipe, you use the best ingredients. I have transitioned from using all-in-one amps to using amps that do one thing really, really well: clean tone. Each guitar responds to amps and pedals different, so having an amp that plays well with anything is key. Many of the best are no-frills amps that are single-channel. For the purpose of this guide, I&amp;#39;m not going to include any amps over $1500 and they have to be available new.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Best clean tube amps (under $1500):&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/Class30II/&quot;&gt;Peavey Classic 30&lt;/a&gt; (30w, 1x12)&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/DeltaBlue115II/&quot;&gt;Peavey Delta Blue&lt;/a&gt; (30w, 1x15)&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/PrinceRev65/&quot;&gt;Fender &amp;#39;65 Princeton Reverb RI&lt;/a&gt; (15w, 1x12)&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/68DeluxeRev&quot;&gt;Fender &amp;#39;68 Deluxe Reverb RI&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;(22w, 1x12)&lt;br /&gt;
	-&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/65DeluxeRev/&quot;&gt;Fender &amp;#39;65 Deluxe Reverb RI&lt;/a&gt; (22x, 1x12)&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/TwinMaster112/&quot;&gt;Budda Twinmaster &lt;/a&gt;(18w, 1x12)&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/Tweaker40112/&quot;&gt;Egnater Tweaker&lt;/a&gt; (15w, 1x12)&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/AC15C1X/&quot;&gt;Vox AC15&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;or &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/AC15HW1X/&quot;&gt;Handwired&lt;/a&gt; (15w, 1x12)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Most of these amps have reverb built in, but others (like some vintage Fenders like the Princeton and Deluxe) do not. Not everyone plays with it (I do 50% of the time), but if you like the bulk it adds to your cleans this isn&amp;#39;t an issue at all - some of the best reverb can be gotten from a box (list below not including the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/63TubeRevBT/&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;63 Fender Tube Reverb&lt;/a&gt;, because of portability issues).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Best Reverb Pedals&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/HolyGrailN/&quot;&gt;Electro-Harmonix Holy Grail&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;(New $120-150 Used: $65+)&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/HallOfFame/&quot;&gt;TC Electronics Hall of Fame&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;(New: $150)&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sweetwater.com/store/detail/FauxSpringRev/&quot;&gt;Wampler Faux Spring Reverb&lt;/a&gt; (New: $230)&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mattsmusic.com/STRYBLUESKY-prod.html&quot;&gt;Strymon Blue Sky Reverb&lt;/a&gt; (New: $300)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Another option is using that solid-state amp that you already have and faking the clean tube amp sound with an &amp;quot;always on&amp;quot; pedal. These with the gain rolled way down give the harmonic complexity you&amp;#39;d get from a tube amp while letting you dial in no overdrive at all to &amp;quot;Tweed Fender turned past 6 o&amp;#39;clock&amp;quot;. The best &amp;#39;fakers&amp;#39; are actual tube preamps.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Best Non-Tube &amp;#39;Color Boxes&amp;#39;&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wamplerpedals.com/heritage/black-65.html&quot;&gt;Wampler Black 65&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.stevesmusiccenter.net/products/toadworks-li-l-leo-overdrive&quot;&gt;Toadworks Lil Leo&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Best Tube &amp;#39;Color Boxes&amp;#39;&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.tonetronix.com/p/SIB-Varidrive.html&quot;&gt;SIB Varidrive&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.effectrode.com/blackbird-vacuum-tube-preamp/&quot;&gt;Blackbird Preamp&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	- &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.stephensonamps.com/stage-hog.htm&quot;&gt;Stephenson Stage Hog&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
